            <h2>Class II Strong Verbs</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">C</span>lass II verbs have an '<strong>eo</strong>' or
                '<strong>u</strong>' followed by a consonant in the root of the verb.
                When they conjugate, they follow the vowel change pattern
                <strong>ēo - ēa - u</strong> or <strong>ū - ēa - u</strong>.
                This means that the root vowel in the present is either '<strong>eo</strong>' or '<strong>u</strong>',
                the root vowel in the past singular is '<strong>ea</strong>', and the root vowel in the past pural is
                '<strong>u</strong>'. So '<em>ic beode - I command</em>', becomes '<em>ic bead - I commanded</em>' or
                '<em>hie budon - they commanded</em>'.
            </p>
            <p>
                Class II Strong Verbs have a further vowel change visible in the
                2nd person singular and 3rd person singular, as the '<strong>eo</strong>' changes
                to '<strong>ie</strong>' and the '<strong>u</strong>' changes to '<strong>y</strong>'. This is
                due to i-Mutation. (See <a href="wam4" class="darkorange-text">i-mutation</a> for more information.) To
                see the vowel
                change, examine the verb '<em>brucan</em>' in the following sentences: '<em>Ðu brycst ðines hlafes - You
                    enjoy your bread
                </em>' and '<em>Ðu giefstolas bruce - You enjoyed gifts</em>'.
            </p>
